                "name": "Elinor Greenberg",
                "href": "/profile/Elinor-Greenberg"
            },
            "answer_text": "Are Narcissists critical of other people? One can think of Narcissism as a self-esteem regulation disorder in which the person has: An unstable sense of selfUnstable self-esteemA lack of empathy for other peopleThese three traits combine to create a situation that causes Narcissists to be unable to accept the blame when something goes wrong. If they did allow themselves to feel at fault, their self-esteem would dip, their sense of identity would shift into their seeing themselves as irredeemably flawed, and they would sink into a shame-based self hating depression. To avoid this, they shift the blame, and instead become extremely critical of other people. Their basic stance is: If something goes wrong, someone else must be blamed.When they feel unhappy about something, it is someone else\u2019s fault.Other people could be doing everything better.Elinor Greenberg, PhD, CGP In private practice in NYC and the author of the book: Borderline, Narcissistic, and Schizoid Adaptations: The Pursuit of Love, Admiration, and Safety. www.elinorgreenberg.com ",
